        <odd id="ref7">
            <head>Early American History Note</head>
            <p>This volume contains an assortment of essays presumably written by Samuel Rush. The topics are wide ranging and cover many cultural and social issues of the day. The opening essay critiques “public singers,” while others touch on suicide, music, and public life.</p>
        </odd>
        <acqinfo id="ref5">
            <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition note</head>
            <p>Purchased ($70.00) and accessioned, 1943 (1943 84466).</p>
        </acqinfo>
        <bioghist id="ref3">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>Samuel Rush was a lawyer, recorder of Philadelphia, and the son of Benjamin Rush.</p>
